"Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Massachusetts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 12:05:30 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/video/2013/apr/20/boston-dzhokhar-tsarnaev-capture-video") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T12:05:30Z") (dc:type nil "Video") (dc:identifier nil "407565707") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon bombing, Boston, Massachusetts, United States, World news") (media:group nil (media:content ((fileSize . "6076944") (type . "video/mp4") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/truemainwebsite/2013/4/20mainwebsite/2013/4/20/130420WatertownReaction-16x9.mp4"))) (media:content ((fileSize . "5352905") (type . "video/3gpp:small") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/4/20/130420WatertownReaction_3gpSml16x9.3gp"))) (media:content ((type . "video/m3u8") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/4/20/130420WatertownReaction/130420WatertownReaction.m3u8"))) (media:content ((fileSize . "22383632") (type . "video/mp4:720") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/4/20/130420WatertownReaction-720.mp4")))) (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2013/4/20/1366457692006/People-wave-U.S.-flags-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Shannon Stapleton/Reuters") (media:description nil "People wave U.S. flags Photograph: Shannon Stapleton/Reuters")))) ("Dove's 'real beauty sketches' ad deserves some praise | Heather Long" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/11704?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Adove-real-beauty-sketches-ad-women-perfection%3A1896805&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Advertising+%28media%29%2CBeauty%2CUnilever+%28Business%29%2CWomen+and+women%27s+interests%2CGender+%28News%29%2CMedia%2CFeminism+%28World+news%29&c5=Fashion+and+Beauty%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBusiness+Markets%2CMedia+Weekly%2CWomen%2CAdvertising+Media&c6=Heather+Long&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+01%3A00&c8=1896805&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Comment+is+free&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Dove%27s+%27real+beauty+sketches%27+ad+deserves+some+praise&c66=Comment+is+free&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FComment+is+free%2FComment+is+free%2Fblog%2FComment+is+free\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Dove's latest campaign to get women to be more confident about their looks makes a powerful point, even if it's only skin deep</p><p>If you haven't seen it already, it's worth the three minutes of your life to watch <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XpaOjMXyJGk\">Dove's new ad</a>, if only because it has sparked such a wide range of reactions. Some women wept at the end of it, immediately sending it to friends with \"you must watch this\" notes; others have gotten <a href=\"http://jazzylittledrops.tumblr.com/post/48118645174/why-doves-real-beauty-sketches-video-makes-me\">downright angry about it</a>. </p><p>Let's start with the obvious: it's an ad, not a film festival documentary. It's been edited heavily and has overly melodramatic music. And yes, at the end of the day, it's trying to sell something, although it's striking that no Dove products are mentioned during the entire three-minute clip, and the Dove brand itself isn't even flashed on the screen until the final seconds. But all the cheesiness doesn't take away from its powerful message: women are too often their own worst critics.</p><p>The ad follows a<a href=\"http://realbeautysketches.dove.us/\"> forensic artist</a>, one of those people who draws crime suspects based on witnesses' descriptions. In this case, he draws facial portraits of several women based solely on what they tell him. He can't see them. Then he draws pictures of the same women based on what people who have only interacted with them for a short while describe. In almost every case, there's a stark difference between the two images of each woman.</p><p>The self-described portraits are uglier, sadder and almost sour-looking in some instances. When the artist asks an African-American woman what her most prominent feature is, she says, \"I have a fat, rounder face,\" immediately honing in on the negative. Several females bemoan their ageing: crows feet around the eyes, more freckles. You can only imagine what they would have said if the portraits were full-body. </p><p>This isn't novel. Plenty of studies have concluded that women tend to view themselves as worse-looking than they are. In an oft-cited 2003 research project, young women were asked to pick out their body image from a range of figures. On average, they picked figures that were <a href=\"http://www.lifeclinic.com/fullpage.aspx?prid=514285&type=1\">11lb (5kg) heavier than their actual weight</a> (young men, by contrast, picked out a figure that was \"better\" than reality). </p><p>Most of us don't need formal studies to know this. Just think about the last few times you've complimented a female on her appearance. More often than not, you get something back along the lines of \"Oh, this old dress/shirt/purse?\" or \"Thanks, but …\" or \"My hairdresser/friend helped me.\" We are constantly diminishing ourselves or attributing our good aspects to the influence of someone or something else.</p><p>Appearances shouldn't matter so much, but they do. One of the loudest criticisms about the Dove ad has been the line where one woman says: </p><blockquote><p>\"I should be more grateful of my natural beauty. It impacts the choices and friends that we make, the jobs we apply for, how we treat our children. It impacts everything. It couldn't be more central to your happiness.\"</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.rawrach.com/2013/04/raw-adjective-7-brutally-or-grossly_17.html\">Blogger Raw Rach just can't seem to understand</a> why some women are unable to say \"f that\" to societal pressure and move on: \"I wanna grab onto their shoulders and shake them and say: get over it already. Chuck the fear.\" It's a noble sentiment, but we do live in visual world, one that is only further enhanced by social media and our camera phones. </p><p>Jean Kilbourne, an author, critic and creator of the <a href=\"http://www.jeankilbourne.com/videos/\">Killing Us Softly film series</a> has studied images of women in the media and pop culture for decades. She says:</p><blockquote><p>\"I think hands down the biggest challenge for young women today is trying to have a healthy self image in a toxic cultural environment.… Dove is owned by Unilever, and some of the products being sold are really stupid like cellulite firming cream. Even so, I still think there's such a paucity of images out there that in any way break away, raise issues or present women in a different way, even if you aren't perfect.\"</p></blockquote><p>Attacking the Dove ad as part of this \"toxic\" environment sends the wrong message. If we want to point fingers, let's start with the <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v7ZLjWkYmr8\">GoDaddy Super Bowl ad</a>, just about any fragrance ad featuring heavily photoshopped models in sexually suggestive photos or<a href=\"http://www.nbc.com/ready-for-love/\"> TV series like Ready for Love</a> that have women declare their undying affection for men they haven't even met.</p><p>Dove's underlying message is you are more beautiful than you think. Be more confident. Frankly, it's refreshing to see an ad that tackles a genuine societal problem head-on, let alone marketing that doesn't try to turn women into sex objects, overburdened housewives or shopaholics.</p><p>Critics of the Dove ad who argue that it holds up white features as ideal make a valid point. Even when the \"strangers\" describe the women, they often use terms like smaller chins and bluer eyes as compliments. Dove should take this to heart in their next go-around. But the point remains: women, whatever their skin tone, should be happier with themselves. </p><p>It's been a hard couple of months, if not couple of years, for women. If we aren't getting told our physical appearance is lacking by the media and advertising, we're getting a lecture from some high-profile figure or another about how we aren't living up to our career potential or finding that elusive \"balance\" in our life. We always lack something, and advertisers can't wait to inform us that one product will make all the difference.</p><p>We know that marketing is false. Yet we are too quick to blame our own shortcomings, as if we were the only ones out there who don't fit the superwoman, supermodel mold. </p><p>Dove put a crack in that veneer. That's the reason the ad has been shared widely. That's the reason some cried right along with the participant who <a href=\"http://realbeautysketches.dove.us/\">admitted she's got a lot of work to do</a> on her self-confidence. Writing those views off as weak or unfeminist, as some have done, is counterproductive.</p><p>Instead of picking the ad apart, applaud it for what it is – and ask for an even better encore.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/advertising\">Advertising</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/fashion/beauty\">Beauty</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/unilever\">Unilever</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/women\">Women</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/gender\">Gender</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/feminism\">Feminism</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/heather-long\">Heather Long</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/20/dove-real-beauty-sketches-ad-women-perfection" (20850 33600) new 5 nil nil ((title nil "Dove's 'real beauty sketches' ad deserves some praise | Heather Long") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/20/dove-real-beauty-sketches-ad-women-perfection") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/11704?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Adove-real-beauty-sketches-ad-women-perfection%3A1896805&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Advertising+%28media%29%2CBeauty%2CUnilever+%28Business%29%2CWomen+and+women%27s+interests%2CGender+%28News%29%2CMedia%2CFeminism+%28World+news%29&c5=Fashion+and+Beauty%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBusiness+Markets%2CMedia+Weekly%2CWomen%2CAdvertising+Media&c6=Heather+Long&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+01%3A00&c8=1896805&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Comment+is+free&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Dove%27s+%27real+beauty+sketches%27+ad+deserves+some+praise&c66=Comment+is+free&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FComment+is+free%2FComment+is+free%2Fblog%2FComment+is+free\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Dove's latest campaign to get women to be more confident about their looks makes a powerful point, even if it's only skin deep</p><p>If you haven't seen it already, it's worth the three minutes of your life to watch <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XpaOjMXyJGk\">Dove's new ad</a>, if only because it has sparked such a wide range of reactions. Some women wept at the end of it, immediately sending it to 