tional domestic arrangements – they also have five snakes – soon seem completely normal, perhaps because they are all so at ease with each other.</p><p>\"A lot of people looking at this from the outside would probably see you as&nbsp;the long-suffering wife,\" says Sarah to Sylvia.</p><p>\"None of the gender or poly stuff has ever been a problem,\" replies Sylvia. \"Irritating personal habits are far worse.\"</p><p>Sylvia admits she felt \"a little bit excluded\" when Sarah and Zoe were going through transition – \"I could never quite know what it was like\" – but this period also helped her bond with Zoe: they both worried about Sarah's operation.</p><p>What about polyamory, though? \"We had a lot to gain and nothing to lose really,\" says Sylvia. \"Transition made my relationship with Sarah that&nbsp;much stronger because we'd been&nbsp;through so much together, so it&nbsp;was like, well, we can do anything after&nbsp;this.\"</p><p>Sarah, Sylvia and Zoe are not \"poly-evangelists\" but simply say it works for them. \"Some people are quite jealous or need that level of commitment from&nbsp;one person that you can't get in a&nbsp;poly relationship so it doesn't suit everyone,\" says Zoe.</p><p>Isn't three fundamentally an awkward number? \"It can be really handy,\" says Sylvia. \"If two of us are massively disagreeing about whether to do something around the house, we can have someone to break the deadlock. As long as you're careful enough so it doesn't end up with two people picking on one.\"</p><p>\"We're all adult enough not to do that,\" adds Sarah.</p><p>Their relationship is&nbsp;a \"triangle\" (a&nbsp;\"V-shaped\" polyamorous relationship in which not all three members of the relationship are connected would be more tricky, they say), and they share many passions. Zoe and Sylvia go <a href=\"http://www.geocaching.com/\" title=\"\">geocaching</a> together; Sarah and Zoe go horseriding. All three women have Lib Dem politics (Zoe hopes to become the first openly trans person to stand for parliament for a&nbsp;major political party) and computing in&nbsp;common. They also enjoy climbing, mountaineering and canyoning together. With Zoe already having three children, they are not planning any more. \"I'm not into children,\" says Sylvia decisively.</p><p>\"I've got three already,\" adds Zoe. And Sarah? \"Governed by the other two really,\" she laughs.</p><p></p><p>Zoe maintains a good relationship with her ex-wife and sees their two daughters and son every weekend; she, Sarah and Sylvia usually stay with them at Zoe's parents house. As children tend to be, hers are very accepting (they don't call her Mum or Dad – simply Zoe) although Zoe admits to feeling bad if \"they get some stick\" at school. \"They were too young to understand gender when I transitioned and when the three of us got together they just mentally shrugged,\" she says. \"It is normal to them.\"</p><p>Zoe has had no problems in the Territorial Army either, but it has been harder to gain acceptance from older family members. While Zoe has an excellent relationship with her parents and her brother, Sarah has been estranged from her father since her transition, although her relationship with her mother is \"better than it's ever been\". Sylvia's mother is \"accepting\", but her grandparents struggled to adapt to her husband becoming her female civil partner, although Sylvia and Sarah were reconciled with them before they died.</p><p>Living in Cambridge, they rarely experience discrimination or abuse. Sarah is not the city's first openly trans councillor, and when they pop down to their local real-ale pub: \"No one bats an eyelid. We're probably some of the less 'out there' people,\" says Zoe.</p><p>They do not hide their living arrangements but Zoe says they invariably develop a language of \"partners\" and other careful phrasing to avoid having to constantly explain themselves. \"If your living arrangements or social situation is abnormal, you don't just come out once, you come out all the time,\" she says. But occasionally it can be fun to observe people's reactions. \"I come out as trans first and then bisexual,\" says Zoe. \"Just when people are getting really confused you hit them with 'poly' and their mind just explodes.\"</p><p>All three women feel liberated by their different experiences of transition and they know quite a few trans people now living polyamorous lives. \"Gender transition is one of the most sexually taboo things you can do, and you do it and you realise the world doesn't end. Then you start thinking, what other things have I always taken for granted that are just wrong?\" says Sarah. \"In some ways I resent being born trans because it's been a lot of pain, a lot of hassle, and it has dominated my life. But at other times I almost feel grateful because it has given me an attitude that almost nothing is sacred and I don't have to be a prisoner to this very English 'mustn't make a fuss, mustn't challenge things' life of quiet desperation.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/family\">Family</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/transgender\">Transgender</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/sex\">Sex</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/gender\">Gender</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/sexuality\">Sexuality</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/patrickbarkham\">Patrick Barkham</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Family") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Life and style") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Transgender") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Sex") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Gender") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Sexuality") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Society") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 06:59:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2013/apr/20/greatest-sexual-taboo-polyamorous-transgender") (dc:creator nil "Patrick Barkham") (dc:subject nil "Life and style") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T06:59:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407271379") (media:keywords nil "Family, Life and style, Transgender, Sex, Gender, World news, Sexuality, Society") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/16/1366108542641/Zoe-OConnell-Sarah-Brown--005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Sarah Lee/Guardian") (media:description nil "Zoe O'Connell (left), Sarah Brown (centre) and Sylvia Knight who live with together in a polyamorous relationship. Photograph: Sarah Lee for the Guardian")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/16/1366108549690/Zoe-OConnell-Sarah-Brown--010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Sarah Lee/Guardian") (media:description nil "Zoe O'Connell, left, Sarah Brown, centre, and Sylvia Knight, who live together in a polyamorous relationship. Photograph: Sarah Lee for the Guardian")))) ("Stephen Lawrence 20 years on: 'I thought there was nothing I could do'" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91480?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Astephen-lawrence-20-years-on%3A1896741&ch=UK+news&c3=Guardian&c4=Stephen+Lawrence+%28News%29%2CUK+news%2CPolice+and+policing%2CRace+issues+%28News%29&c5=Society+Weekly%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Jemima+Kiss&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+07%3A01&c8=1896741&c9=Article&c10=News%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Stephen+Lawrence+20+years+on%3A+%27I+thought+there+was+nothing+I+could+do%27&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FUK+news%2FStephen+Lawrence\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Alexandra Marie's life changed for ever 20 years ago, when she looked on in horror as a black teenager was stabbed to death</p><p>Alexandra Marie was 19 when she first came to England as an au pair. A bright, tenacious young Frenchwoman, she had a flair for languages and excelled at school but decided to leave Rouen University in her second year to improve her spoken English. She had struck gold with a kind host family in south London who made her feel at home, taking her on family holidays to Cornwall and Dorset. A month or so into her stay, her French boyfriend came to visit, and it was after taking him back to Charing Cross station one Thursday evening that Marie's life changed irreparably.</p><p>There was a bus strike that night, 22 April 1993, and she was having trouble getting home. Outside Eltham station the 286 bus stopped, the driver helpfully asking Marie where she needed to get to. While they talked, two young black men ran up and the driver opened the back doors to let them on. Eighteen-year-old Stephen Lawrence and his friend Duwayne Brooks boarded the bus.</p><p>Today Marie is tucked up on her sofa, gripping a strong cup of coffee, at her home deep in French wine country. Now an English teacher, she speaks fluently but with a strong accent, pausing occasionally to check more complex words in a thick dictionary to make sure her point is made precisely. She retells her story with calm and focus, sifting documentation from a meticulously well-ordered cupboard of files, diaries and photographs. But often she becomes more animated, raising her voice and throwing out questions, and this happens when she talks about Lawrence.</p><p>The driver made an unscheduled stop that night in 1993, to let Marie off at the roundabout in Well Hall Road. He told her to wait for a 161 or 122 to Woolwich. Lawrence, Brooks and another passenger, Royston Westbrook, also got out and headed to the same bus stop.</p><p>They waited together for several minutes. Marie remembers those moments vividly and has revisited them many times over the past 20 years. \"They looked young and cool, and I thought they looked very happy. I even thought they were doing dance steps. There was no aggression in them at all. They just looked like young men I would be happy to know.\"</p><p>Marie shuffled forward to let Lawrence read the timetable behind her. \"A couple of minutes,\" he said to Brooks. She crouched on the kerb, smoking a cigarette to make herself feel more assured, she recalls. Another man, Joseph Shepherd, walked up to the stop. Moments later, impatient, and with Lawrence anxious to get home, he and his friend walked back towards the roundabout to see if they could see a bus approaching.</p><p>From her position at the bus stop, Marie could see the pair walk down the hill. A moment later, a few yards apart, they turned back. Some sudden movement attracted her attention, a commotion, and she could see Lawrence on the ground, a group of men surrounding him and kicking, holding him down, she remembers.</p><p>That the attack was over in less than 10 seconds betrays how brutal and violent it really was, a knife severing two arteries and piercing a lung. Lawrence had minutes to live.</p><p>Marie and the two men at the bus stop saw Lawrence pick himself up and, leaving his bag on the floor, run up the hill on the other side of the road after Brooks. \"Oh, ça va,\" she said to herself, assuming that as he was running, he must be OK. She lost sight of them and the bus finally arrived.</p><p>As the bus passed Lawrence, passengers looked down from the window to see him collapsed on the pavement, a small group gathered around him.</p><p>Marie remembers the bus stopping again and two more men got on – one of them agitated, breathless and with bad teeth. One handed something to the other, then ran off the bus to where Lawrence was lying, as if to check something, and then ran back again. He took something back from the other man.</p><p>\"I wondered if I should get down off the bus but I thought that there was nothing I could do to help, so I stayed,\" she said. \"I saw that Stephen was lying on the floor, but this image is so upsetting because now I know he was dying.\"</p><p>A young couple heading home from a church service, Conor and Louise Taaffe, were among those who had stopped to help Lawrence. the last words he heard as Mrs Taaffe held his head in her hands were: \"You are loved. You are loved.\"</p><p>Two days later, Marie was thumbing through a newspaper in a Dorset cottage on a weekend away with her host family. She began reading about a young black man murdered at a bus stop in south London, realising with horror that this was the attack she had seen on the Thursday night. Struggling to talk, she showed the paper to the family, who sat her down with a brandy and phoned the police on her behalf.</p><p>\"24 April: Dorset, lu journal. Ai appris pour le meurtre … Choc,\" read the short note in her diary that night, in her delicate écriture cursive hand. She spent three hours with the police the following Monday and six hours with the police two weeks later. She remembers they were attentive, the translator putting her at ease by rattling off tales of working for the footballer Eric Cantona.</p><p>On that day in 1993, a sketch artist drew an image of the aggressive man she says she saw on the bus but she was not happy with it; five years later she saw a picture of a snarling David Norris being pelted with eggs leaving the public inquiry – an expression that, she said, looked like the man she had seen on the bus. \"Norris said he wasn't in the area, but they didn't give me a chance to go to the identity parade, even to eliminate anyone.\"</p><p>The Lawrence case has arguably been the most high-profile in the history of the Metropolitan police, dogged from the outset by incompetence, corruption and racism. A lack of evidence led the initial 1994 case to collapse, and a private prosecution by Lawrence's parents failed in 1996 after evidence was ruled inadmissible.</p><p>An insubstantial 1997 inquiry found \"weaknesses\" but no racism, prompting a more robust judicial review from Sir William Macpherson that found \"professional incompetence, institutional racism and a failure of leadership\". As a consequence of the case, the government scrapped the double jeopardy legal principle in 2005, allowing suspects to be tried twice for the same crime. In 2008, cold-case scientists found a minute spot of Lawrence's blood on Gary Dobson's jacket, prompting a full retrial in 2011. In January 2012 Dobson and Norris, two of the original five suspects, were finally found guilty of the murder and sentenced to life in prison.</p><p>The Met said it would not be appropriate to comment on Marie's story because of ongoing lines of inquiry. Outside of the trials, Marie has had little communication with the police over the past 20 years, though one senior officer has stayed in contact and continued to support her. Despite this, no one has yet explained why she was not invited to join Royston Westbrook and Joseph Shepherd at that first ID parade or explained who the two men on the bus really were.</p><p>Her host family were very supportive in the first months after the murder in 1993, but she was struggling to process the shock of that night and it weighed heavily on her young mind. Why had Lawrence been attacked? What was the real motivation of those young white men? Should she have gone to help him as he lay on the street?</p><p>Back in Normandy that September, her parents and friends were uncomfortable listening to what had happened, and didn't realise the significance of a high-profile murder which had savaged the credibility of policing and raised racial tensions in the UK. She describes the sense of <em>pudique</em>, the French version of a stiff upper lip. \"Sometimes with friends I would say I had been the witness of a murder but people didn't want to hear about it, didn't know what to do with that information. I felt very isolated. They told me to stop thinking about it so I had to bury it inside, like a family secret.\"</p><p>Marie's life drifted through trauma into denial and beyond. She began to seek out friendship and recognition from black friends, constructing a naive world in which white people were bad and black people good. \"If I hadn't witnessed Stephen Lawrence's murder I wouldn't have been so interested in seeking out black stories and black people. It changed my world.\" She moved, with her mixed-race boyfriend, to the racially diverse Réunion island in the Indian Ocean, where she started university. There she found an academic release in writing about the new politics of multiculturalism and applied for a grant to study in South Africa for three months.</p><p>Marie, then 23, was caught up in the excitement and optimism of post-apartheid South Africa, but also acknowledges she was naive and put herself at risk, spending time in the ghettos of Cape Town, where she was often the only white, western face. One day, a man she had interviewed held a knife to her throat, holding her captive for 10 days and only releasing her when the French embassy came looking for her. She fled back to Réunion and knows she was lucky to escape with her life.</p><p>\"I was very young and naive, trying to open my heart to people,\" said Marie. \"South Africa is a very violent place now and very different to what they were dreaming, but I wanted to understand how apartheid had developed and how it had been defeated. And I suppose I was trying to understand why there was racism in the world.\"</p><p>Marie completed her masters degree and struck up a relationship with a well-known black musician who gave her love, support and understanding at a time when she was incredibly vulnerable. They had a child in 2002, but she says the relationship became destructive and she moved back to France. Five years on, Marie and her former partner have an amicable relationship and he sees his son regularly, but she had to live through yet more trauma to get to this point.</p><p>Throughout her struggle runs the thread of Lawrence's story. Marie testified as a witness at the first trial in 1996, which collapsed due to lack of evidence. She returned to talk to police in 2000 but was overwhelmed by returning to the bus stop and her memory blanked. The image of Lawrence lying collapsed on that street has continued to haunt her.</p><p>Her work with a specialist trauma psychologist uses a technique which explores and neutralises these kinds of traumatic memories. It has clearly been powerful and effective for Marie, who says she would be dead had it not been for her emotional resourcefulness. \"I had never really cried until that first session in 2011. I kept it all inside. I talked about feeling guilty, about not being able to help him. It had been like a boomerang. I wanted to throw everything away from me, but it kept coming back.\"</p><p>The last time the boomerang came back was on a slow day at work in November 2012, when Marie came across an extract from a book by the journalist Brian Cathcart, now well known for his role leading the Hacked Off press campaign. Published in 1999, The Case of Stephen Lawrence has become almost the definitive public record of the murder, but Marie has become near-obsessional about his description of her role that night.</p><p>Cathcart writes that Lawrence and Brooks chased the bus to the Eltham station stop where \"by good fortune … the bus was delayed by a young French woman who was asking the bus driver questions\".</p><p>The phrase \"good fortune\" has tortured her. \"It was the first time I had heard of any delay and I realised that if I hadn't been there, Stephen would not have been able to catch that bus. When I read this, all my guilt and memories came back.</p><p>\"I already felt powerless that night. I couldn't do anything – I was only a young woman. But the bus stopped and the driver asked me which bus I was waiting for. I didn't stop the bus and I didn't cause the delay.\"</p><p>In Marie's mind, the traumatic events of the past 20 years are knitted together, the guilt of one woven to the guilt of the next. The distress caused by what she saw as the blame attributed in Cathcart's book was compounded by her realisation that her name was so public, so indelibly part of the Lawrence story; she had asked for anonymity when first questioned by police in 1993 and no one explained that, unlike in France, she would be identified in open court and in press coverage.</p><p>Cathcart says no one could reasonably believe that catching that bus, or her role in that, was any part of the reason Lawrence was murdered. \"There were a thousand and more contingencies that placed those two young men at that bus stop at that moment,\" he said. \"And of course the responsibility for the murder really lies with the perpetrators.\"</p><p>Marie obsesses over the details of the case; the characters on the bus; whether corrupt police were protecting suspects. Evidence given at the time suggests that Norris did not run on to the bus with Marie that night. Witness B saw Norris, Neil Acourt and two others running out of Cobbett Road – in the opposite direction to the bus, Cathcart points out, while Witness K saw Norris at a nearby house one hour later. Neither of those statements are consistent with taking a bus towards Woolwich.</p><p>On the day that Norris and Dobson were convicted in January 2012, Marie was at work and watched the news, elated, on TV. \"I saw how people were reacting, the relief and the happiness, but I had nobody to celebrate with. Nobody understood what this meant.\"</p><p>The recognition Marie craves is that witnesses are also victims of these crimes. \"If I could talk to my 19-year-old self I would say that there are other ways to repair your life than some sort of black and white quest,\" she says. \"When the police proceedings are all over, you are on your own. Witnesses of violent events can develop traumas and change the way they perceive life, and they need to be supported. It is not an accident – it is a murder and there is no way to explain it to yourself. It follows you like a ghost. And I know I ended up making wrong decisions for myself that I wouldn't otherwise have made.\"</p><p>Now 39, Marie and her son are in a new, comfortable home, a place of peace completely unconnected to the violence of her past. Her life is calmer, reassuringly uneventful, and she wants to move on. For Marie, that means the three remaining suspects – Neil and Jamie Acourt, and Luke Knight – behind bars. \"I want Stephen Lawrence to lie in peace, with his murderers in jail.\"</p><p>It also means a visit to Lawrence's grave in Jamaica to say goodbye; it wasn't until 2011, at the Old Bailey retrial, that she met the Lawrence family and could tell them that she shared their pain. \"I think maybe in life fate gives you what it knows you have the courage to deal with. I do think life is wonderful. It is an amazing thing, to be alive.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/lawrence\">Stephen Lawrence</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/police\">Police</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/race\">Race issues</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/jemimakiss\">Jemima Kiss</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2013/apr/20/stephen-lawrence-20-years-on" (20850 12088) new 18 nil nil ((title nil "Stephen Lawrence 20 years on: 'I thought there was nothing I could do'") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2013/apr/20/stephen-lawrence-20-years-on") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91480?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Astephen-lawrence-20-years-on%3A1896741&ch=UK+news&c3=Guardian&c4=Stephen+Lawrence+%28News%29%2CUK+news%2CPolice+and+policing%2CRace+issues+%28News%29&c5=Society+Weekly%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Jemima+Kiss&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+07%3A01&c8=1896741&c9=Article&c10=News%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Stephen+Lawrence+20+years+on%3A+%27I+thought+there+was+nothing+I+could+do%27&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FUK+news%2FStephen+Lawrence\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Alexandra Marie's life changed for ever 20 years ago, when she looked on in horror as a black teenager was stabbed to death</p><p>Alexandra Marie was 19 when she first came to England as an au pair. A bright, tenacious young Frenchwoman, she had a flair for languages and excelled at school but decided to leave Rouen University in her second year to improve her spoken English. She had struck gold with a kind host