e: \"You are loved. You are loved.\"</p><p>Two days later, Marie was thumbing through a newspaper in a Dorset cottage on a weekend away with her host family. She began reading about a young black man murdered at a bus stop in south London, realising with horror that this was the attack she had seen on the Thursday night. Struggling to talk, she showed the paper to the family, who sat her down with a brandy and phoned the police on her behalf.</p><p>\"24 April: Dorset, lu journal. Ai appris pour le meurtre … Choc,\" read the short note in her diary that night, in her delicate écriture cursive hand. She spent three hours with the police the following Monday and six hours with the police two weeks later. She remembers they were attentive, the translator putting her at ease by rattling off tales of working for the footballer Eric Cantona.</p><p>On that day in 1993, a sketch artist drew an image of the aggressive man she says she saw on the bus but she was not happy with it; five years later she saw a picture of a snarling David Norris being pelted with eggs leaving the public inquiry – an expression that, she said, looked like the man she had seen on the bus. \"Norris said he wasn't in the area, but they didn't give me a chance to go to the identity parade, even to eliminate anyone.\"</p><p>The Lawrence case has arguably been the most high-profile in the history of the Metropolitan police, dogged from the outset by incompetence, corruption and racism. A lack of evidence led the initial 1994 case to collapse, and a private prosecution by Lawrence's parents failed in 1996 after evidence was ruled inadmissible.</p><p>An insubstantial 1997 inquiry found \"weaknesses\" but no racism, prompting a more robust judicial review from Sir William Macpherson that found \"professional incompetence, institutional racism and a failure of leadership\". As a consequence of the case, the government scrapped the double jeopardy legal principle in 2005, allowing suspects to be tried twice for the same crime. In 2008, cold-case scientists found a minute spot of Lawrence's blood on Gary Dobson's jacket, prompting a full retrial in 2011. In January 2012 Dobson and Norris, two of the original five suspects, were finally found guilty of the murder and sentenced to life in prison.</p><p>The Met said it would not be appropriate to comment on Marie's story because of ongoing lines of inquiry. Outside of the trials, Marie has had little communication with the police over the past 20 years, though one senior officer has stayed in contact and continued to support her. Despite this, no one has yet explained why she was not invited to join Royston Westbrook and Joseph Shepherd at that first ID parade or explained who the two men on the bus really were.</p><p>Her host family were very supportive in the first months after the murder in 1993, but she was struggling to process the shock of that night and it weighed heavily on her young mind. Why had Lawrence been attacked? What was the real motivation of those young white men? Should she have gone to help him as he lay on the street?</p><p>Back in Normandy that September, her parents and friends were uncomfortable listening to what had happened, and didn't realise the significance of a high-profile murder which had savaged the credibility of policing and raised racial tensions in the UK. She describes the sense of <em>pudique</em>, the French version of a stiff upper lip. \"Sometimes with friends I would say I had been the witness of a murder but people didn't want to hear about it, didn't know what to do with that information. I felt very isolated. They told me to stop thinking about it so I had to bury it inside, like a family secret.\"</p><p>Marie's life drifted through trauma into denial and beyond. She began to seek out friendship and recognition from black friends, constructing a naive world in which white people were bad and black people good. \"If I hadn't witnessed Stephen Lawrence's murder I wouldn't have been so interested in seeking out black stories and black people. It changed my world.\" She moved, with her mixed-race boyfriend, to the racially diverse Réunion island in the Indian Ocean, where she started university. There she found an academic release in writing about the new politics of multiculturalism and applied for a grant to study in South Africa for three months.</p><p>Marie, then 23, was caught up in the excitement and optimism of post-apartheid South Africa, but also acknowledges she was naive and put herself at risk, spending time in the ghettos of Cape Town, where she was often the only white, western face. One day, a man she had interviewed held a knife to her throat, holding her captive for 10 days and only releasing her when the French embassy came looking for her. She fled back to Réunion and knows she was lucky to escape with her life.</p><p>\"I was very young and naive, trying to open my heart to people,\" said Marie. \"South Africa is a very violent place now and very different to what they were dreaming, but I wanted to understand how apartheid had developed and how it had been defeated. And I suppose I was trying to understand why there was racism in the world.\"</p><p>Marie completed her masters degree and struck up a relationship with a well-known black musician who gave her love, support and understanding at a time when she was incredibly vulnerable. They had a child in 2002, but she says the relationship became destructive and she moved back to France. Five years on, Marie and her former partner have an amicable relationship and he sees his son regularly, but she had to live through yet more trauma to get to this point.</p><p>Throughout her struggle runs the thread of Lawrence's story. Marie testified as a witness at the first trial in 1996, which collapsed due to lack of evidence. She returned to talk to police in 2000 but was overwhelmed by returning to the bus stop and her memory blanked. The image of Lawrence lying collapsed on that street has continued to haunt her.</p><p>Her work with a specialist trauma psychologist uses a technique which explores and neutralises these kinds of traumatic memories. It has clearly been powerful and effective for Marie, who says she would be dead had it not been for her emotional resourcefulness. \"I had never really cried until that first session in 2011. I kept it all inside. I talked about feeling guilty, about not being able to help him. It had been like a boomerang. I wanted to throw everything away from me, but it kept coming back.\"</p><p>The last time the boomerang came back was on a slow day at work in November 2012, when Marie came across an extract from a book by the journalist Brian Cathcart, now well known for his role leading the Hacked Off press campaign. Published in 1999, The Case of Stephen Lawrence has become almost the definitive public record of the murder, but Marie has become near-obsessional about his description of her role that night.</p><p>Cathcart writes that Lawrence and Brooks chased the bus to the Eltham station stop where \"by good fortune … the bus was delayed by a young French woman who was asking the bus driver questions\".</p><p>The phrase \"good fortune\" has tortured her. \"It was the first time I had heard of any delay and I realised that if I hadn't been there, Stephen would not have been able to catch that bus. When I read this, all my guilt and memories came back.</p><p>\"I already felt powerless that night. I couldn't do anything – I was only a young woman. But the bus stopped and the driver asked me which bus I was waiting for. I didn't stop the bus and I didn't cause the delay.\"</p><p>In Marie's mind, the traumatic events of the past 20 years are knitted together, the guilt of one woven to the guilt of the next. The distress caused by what she saw as the blame attributed in Cathcart's book was compounded by her realisation that her name was so public, so indelibly part of the Lawrence story; she had asked for anonymity when first questioned by police in 1993 and no one explained that, unlike in France, she would be identified in open court and in press coverage.</p><p>Cathcart says no one could reasonably believe that catching that bus, or her role in that, was any part of the reason Lawrence was murdered. \"There were a thousand and more contingencies that placed those two young men at that bus stop at that moment,\" he said. \"And of course the responsibility for the murder really lies with the perpetrators.\"</p><p>Marie obsesses over the details of the case; the characters on the bus; whether corrupt police were protecting suspects. Evidence given at the time suggests that Norris did not run on to the bus with Marie that night. Witness B saw Norris, Neil Acourt and two others running out of Cobbett Road – in the opposite direction to the bus, Cathcart points out, while Witness K saw Norris at a nearby house one hour later. Neither of those statements are consistent with taking a bus towards Woolwich.</p><p>On the day that Norris and Dobson were convicted in January 2012, Marie was at work and watched the news, elated, on TV. \"I saw how people were reacting, the relief and the happiness, but I had nobody to celebrate with. Nobody understood what this meant.\"</p><p>The recognition Marie craves is that witnesses are also victims of these crimes. \"If I could talk to my 19-year-old self I would say that there are other ways to repair your life than some sort of black and white quest,\" she says. \"When the police proceedings are all over, you are on your own. Witnesses of violent events can develop traumas and change the way they perceive life, and they need to be supported. It is not an accident – it is a murder and there is no way to explain it to yourself. It follows you like a ghost. And I know I ended up making wrong decisions for myself that I wouldn't otherwise have made.\"</p><p>Now 39, Marie and her son are in a new, comfortable home, a place of peace completely unconnected to the violence of her past. Her life is calmer, reassuringly uneventful, and she wants to move on. For Marie, that means the three remaining suspects – Neil and Jamie Acourt, and Luke Knight – behind bars. \"I want Stephen Lawrence to lie in peace, with his murderers in jail.\"</p><p>It also means a visit to Lawrence's grave in Jamaica to say goodbye; it wasn't until 2011, at the Old Bailey retrial, that she met the Lawrence family and could tell them that she shared their pain. \"I think maybe in life fate gives you what it knows you have the courage to deal with. I do think life is wonderful. It is an amazing thing, to be alive.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/lawrence\">Stephen Lawrence</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/police\">Police</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/race\">Race issues</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/jemimakiss\">Jemima Kiss</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "Stephen Lawrence") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "Police") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Race issues") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 06:01:28 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2013/apr/20/stephen-lawrence-20-years-on") (dc:creator nil "Jemima Kiss") (dc:subject nil "UK news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T06:01:29Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407541191") (media:keywords nil "Stephen Lawrence, UK news, Police, Race issues") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/19/1366394214721/Alexandra-Marie-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Alexandra Marie still has her diary from April 1993 when, as a 19-year-old au pair in south London, she witnessed the racist killing of Stephen Lawrence.")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/19/1366394222801/Alexandra-Marie-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Alexandra Marie still has her diary from April 1993 when, as a 19-year-old au pair in south London, she witnessed the racist killing of Stephen Lawrence.")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366392307629/A-family-photograph-of-St-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PA/Family Handout") (media:description nil "A family photograph of Stephen Lawrence. Photograph: PA")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/19/1366394493102/Stephen-Lawrence-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Ian West/PA") (media:description nil "The bus stop in Eltham, south-east London, where Stephen Lawrence was attacked. Photograph: Ian West/PA")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/19/1366394696340/Gary-Dobson-and-David-Nor-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AFP") (media:description nil "Gary Dobson, left, and David Norris, right, were convicted in January 2012 of Stephen Lawrence's murder. Photograph: AFP")))) ("Gold price slumps as traders face global metals market freefall" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/32718?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Agold-price-slumps%3A1895772&ch=Money&c3=Guardian&c4=Investments+%28Money+-+UK+consumer%29%2CMoney%2CGold+%28Business%29%2CInvesting+%28Business%29%2CCommodities+%28oil+gold+etc%29%2CMining+industry+%28Business+sector%29%2CFinancial+sector+%28business%29%2CBusiness%2CWorld+news%2CUK+news&c5=Personal+Finance%2CBusiness+Markets%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CInvestments+%26+Savings&c6=Patrick+Collinson&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A59&c8=1895772&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Gold+price+slumps+as+traders+face+global+metals+market+freefall&c66=Money&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FMoney%2FMoney%2FInvestments\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The decade-long bull market in the precious metal is over, after hectic selling drags down silver and copper</p><p>The biggest plunge in the gold price for more than 30 years has wiped $1 trillion off the value of global reserves of the precious metal, leaving small investors reeling as popular funds have lost a fifth of their value in just a matter of weeks.</p><p>In hectic selling that began last Friday, the price has dropped from $1,580 an ounce to $1,380, dragging other metals down. Silver has sunk from $28 to $23, while copper is down from $7,500 to $7,100 a tonne.</p><p>Small investors in widely-held funds such as BlackRock Gold & General have suffered. The BlackRock fund, which has £1.6bn under management, has lost 21% of its value over the past month and 36% over the past six months. It invests in the shares of gold and metal mining companies – and these have fared even worse than the gold price.</p><p>Barrick Gold, the world's biggest gold miner, has seen its shares slump on the Toronto stock market from C$55 to just C$19 since last September. Newcrest Mining, an Australian gold miner that is the biggest holding in the BlackRock fund, has fallen from A$30 last September to A$17 this week.</p><p>But Richard Davis, managing director of BlackRock's Natural Resources team, says the fall has to be seen in the context of the long rise in the gold price, which rose 405% between January 2000 and January 2011.</p><p>\"We don't see this sell-off as the beginning of a bear market for the metal,\" he added. \"Longer term, the factors that have driven the bull market in gold have not gone away. We are yet to see the real ramifications of quantitative easing, in terms of inflation.</p><p>\"At the same time, we expect jewellery demand to pick up at these lower prices, especially in China. The recent sell-off has been largely indiscriminate, which has presented us with some excellent buying opportunities for the longer term. We have been adding to several positions in the Gold & General Fund.\"</p><p>But it might be expected for a fund manager to talk up his fund. Another gold market expert, who preferred to remain anonymous, said: \"For a long time the gold price was outperforming the price of shares in gold mining companies, and fund managers were saying the two had to converge. But it just hasn't happened. Very few of them pay a dividend, the costs of extraction have risen sharply, and they are leveraged to the gold price on the way down.\"</p><p>But why has the gold price fallen so far and so suddenly? Some say it was prompted by investment bank Goldman Sachs, which, <a href=\"http://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2013/04/16/goldman-sachs-keep-shorting-gold-go-long-natural-gas/\" title=\"\">last Friday, recommended its clients go \"short\" on gold</a>, slashing its longer-term forecast for the price of gold to $1,270 by end 2014 – a target it has nearly hit already. It marks a <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2012/aug/31/gold-lost-shine-value-fallen\" title=\"\">U-turn from the end of 2011, </a>when Goldman Sachs was telling investors that gold would hit $2,000 an ounce.</p><p>More bearish commentators, such as Viktor Nossek, head of research at exchange traded fund provider Boost, wrote before the recent price crash that gold was heading into a two-decade long bear market. \"We are possibly entering a stage of prolonged weakness in the price of gold,\" he says.</p><p>Some predict that gold is heading back below $1,000 an ounce, and point to charts that suggest similarities with the last crash, between 1980 and 1983, when it fell in price by half and stayed low for another decade. But others suggest darkly that the market has been temporarily rigged by short-sellers.</p><p>Direct selling of gold by British investors has been relatively muted, says Adrian Ash of Bullion Vault, which stores 33m tonnes of gold worth more than £1bn on behalf of 45,000 investors. He says sellers have dumped only 1% of their holdings and that customers turned net buyers by Wednesday this week.</p><p>He blames a range of factors for the sell-off, including the US Federal Reserve's indication that it is less inclined to print more money; news that Cyprus may sell its reserves, possibly followed by other European governments; and a slowdown in Chinese growth. However, he believes fundamentals, remain supportive: \"While we don't see the price suddenly going back up, neither do we see it in the long term falling substantially from the current level.\"</p><p>The good news for the vast majority of people whose only connection with gold is their teeth or their wedding ring, is that the sell-off in commodities has been across the board. The price of oil has also fallen, from $110 a barrel at the beginning of April to $99 this week, finally giving some relief to motorists, with all the major supermarket chains cutting pump prices by 2p-3p a litre.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/moneyinvestments\">Investments</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/gold\">Gold</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/investing\">Investing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/commodities\">Commodities</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/mining\">Mining</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-sector\">Financial sector</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/patrickcollinson\">Patrick Collinson</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2013/apr/20/gold-price-slumps" (20850 11941) new 19 nil nil ((title nil "Gold price slumps as traders face global metals market freefall") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2013/apr/20/gold-price-slumps") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/32718?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Agold-price-slumps%3A1895772&ch=Money&c3=Guardian&c4=Investments+%28Money+-+UK+consumer%29%2CMoney%2CGold+%28Business%29%2CInvesting+%28Business%29%2CCommodities+%28oil+gold+etc%29%2CMining+industry+%28Business+sector%29%2CFinancial+sector+%28business%29%2CBusiness%2CWorld+news%2CUK+news&c5=Personal+Finance%2CBusiness+Markets%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CInvestments+%26+Savings&c6=Patrick+Collinson&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A59&c8=1895772&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=